Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} over high heat. Once hot, add the @diced chicken thigh{260%g}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and cook, stirring regularly, until golden brown, ~{5-6%minutes}. Transfer to a #plate{} and set aside. Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Return the #saucepan{} to the heat, add the onion and season with @salt{}. Cook, stirring regularly, until soft and golden, ~{8-10%minutes}. Add the garlic, @North Indian Style Spice Mix{1%tsp} and @ground cumin{1%tsp} and cook for ~{2%minutes}, stirring regularly.

Add the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @chicken stock powder{1} and @water{200%ml} and the @red split lentils{50%g}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, stir well and bring to a simmer. Cover with a #lid{} (or some foil) and simmer until the lentils are tender and almost cooked, ~{15%minutes}. Preheat your #oven{} to 180°C.

Once the lentils have cooked for ~{15%minutes}, return the chicken to the saucepan and mix into the dal. Cover with a lid again and cook until the lentils are soft and the chicken is cooked through, ~{6-8%minutes}. Add a splash of water if it is starting to dry out.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Pop the @plain naans{2} on a #baking tray{} and bake until warmed through, ~{3-4%minutes}. Add the @baby spinach{125%g} to the dal a handful at a time until it is completely wilted, ~{2-3%minutes}. Taste and add more @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

Divide the dal between #bowls{} and serve with the naans. Enjoy!